Calendars.

A calendar tells the player the current date. Stand on a calendar, press the interact key, and it speaks a lead-in you chose followed by the date. It plays a quiet ambient loop the whole time it's there, so the player can find it by ear. A calendar is essentially a sign that ends with the live date instead of fixed words — it's identical to a clock in every way except that it announces the date rather than the time.

A calendar is built in two variants, chosen from the build mode list: a single calendar (one tile) and a ranged calendar (a rectangular area the player can read from anywhere inside).

How a calendar works.

A calendar with a sound theme plays its ambient loop across its area for as long as it exists, so the player can hear where it is — like a clock, and unlike a sign, a calendar always loops. While the player is inside it and presses the interact key, the calendar plays a press cue and speaks its text immediately followed by the current date. If the calendar is destroyable, bombs and projectiles can smash it; it plays a break sound and is gone.

Calendar fields.

The calendar form takes the following:

Coordinates. A single calendar takes an x and y (and z on 3d maps); a ranged calendar takes a minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), chosen with the ranged option in the build mode list.
Text. The lead-in spoken just before the date, which defaults to "The date is ". The current date is appended to it automatically when the calendar is read.
Calendar sound (a folder name from the calendar sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the ambient loop, a press cue (played on a read), and a break cue (played when the calendar is destroyed). Pick none for a silent calendar.
Destroyable (checkbox). When checked, the calendar can be smashed by bombs and projectiles; when unchecked, it's permanent.

A clock is the same object built for the current time instead of the date; see the clocks topic.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the calendar sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the press clip of the highlighted theme and hold control and press L to hear its ambient loop.

Authoring calendars by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a single calendar is: calendar x y "text" calendartype destroyable. On 3d maps a z follows y: calendar x y z "text" calendartype destroyable. A ranged calendar replaces the single tile with minimum and maximum pairs: calendar minx maxx miny maxy "text" calendartype destroyable, inserting a minimum and maximum z after the y pair on 3d maps. The text is wrapped in double quotes, destroyable is the literal word true or false, and the calendar sound must match a calendar sounds folder name or the word none.
